In the men's events, the individual épée saw [Rubén Limardo](/Rub%C3%A9n_Limardo) of [Venezuela](/Venezuela_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) claim gold, a testament to his tactical patience and strength, denying José Domínguez of [Argentina](/Argentina_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) the top spot. The team épée event further solidified Venezuela's dominance in this weapon, with the Limardo brothers, Rubén and Francisco, alongside [Silvio Fernández](/Silvio_Fern%C3%A1ndez_(fencer_born_1979)), forming an impenetrable unit. The United States, however, showed its depth by securing gold in both individual and team foil, with [Alexander Massialas](/Alexander_Massialas) and [Gerek Meinhardt](/Gerek_Meinhardt) leading the charge, showcasing the rapid, precise movements characteristic of foil fencing. [Eli Dershwitz](/Eli_Dershwitz) of the [United States](/United_States_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) demonstrated the explosive power required for sabre, clinching the individual gold, a performance echoed by the US team in the men's team sabre, where [Daryl Homer](/Daryl_Homer) and [Jeff Spear](/Jeff_Spear) added their formidable skills. Canada's [Joseph Polossifakis](/Joseph_Polossifakis) put up a commendable fight, earning silver in individual sabre, a hard-won accolade in a fiercely contested discipline.

