The women’s events were equally compelling, showcasing a fusion of grace and aggression. [Katharine Holmes](/Katharine_Holmes) secured gold for the [United States](/United_States_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) in individual épée, with Violeta Ramírez Peguero of the [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Republic_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) earning a notable silver. The US team, comprising [Anna van Brummen](/Anna_van_Brummen), [Katharine Holmes](/Katharine_Holmes), and [Katarzyna Trzopek](/Katarzyna_Trzopek), further solidified their position in team épée, proving that collective strategy can be as sharp as an individual blade.

In individual foil, [Lee Kiefer](/Lee_Kiefer) of the [United States](/United_States_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) showcased her exceptional speed and precision, earning gold. However, in a turn of events that likely delighted the home crowd, [Canada](/Canada_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) claimed gold in women's team foil, with [Alanna Goldie](/Alanna_Goldie), [Eleanor Harvey](/Eleanor_Harvey), and [Kelleigh Ryan](/Kelleigh_Ryan) delivering a performance that truly resonated. This was a significant victory for the host nation, demonstrating their ability to contend with the established powerhouses. The sabre events saw [Dagmara Wozniak](/Dagmara_Wozniak) of the [United States](/United_States_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) win individual gold, a testament to her aggressive style and tactical prowess. The US continued its sabre dominance in the team event, with a powerful lineup including [Ibtihaj Muhammad](/Ibtihaj_Muhammad), [Dagmara Wozniak](/Dagmara_Wozniak), and the legendary [Mariel Zagunis](/Mariel_Zagunis), a formidable trio whose experience and skill proved insurmountable. [Alejandra Benítez](/Alejandra_Ben%C3%ADtez) of [Venezuela](/Venezuela_at_the_2015_Pan_American_Games) consistently performed, earning silver in individual sabre and contributing to her nation's bronze in the team event.

